]]></description>
										<content:encoded><!--[CDATA[<div class="wp-block-image is-style-center-align-caption"-->
<figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Wasson-16-x-9-1024x576.jpg" alt="Dr. Megan Wasson, surgery, endometriosis," class="wp-image-348600" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Wasson-16-x-9-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Wasson-16-x-9-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Wasson-16-x-9-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Wasson-16-x-9-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2022/09/Wasson-16-x-9.jpg 1920w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dr. Megan Wasson in the operating room</figcaption></figure>


<p>A hysterectomy can treat many gynecologic conditions, including fibroids, painful periods and cancer, such as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/endometrial-cancer/symptoms-causes/syc-20352461" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">endometrial</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/discussion/toolkit-for-reducing-cervical-cancer-risk/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">cervical</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/ovarian-cancer/symptoms-causes/syc-20375941" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ovarian&nbsp;</a>and uterine cancers.</p>



<p><a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/biographies/wasson-megan-n-d-o/bio-20234473?_ga=2.26311997.16198988.1507659618-218178136.1502116314?mc_id=us&amp;utm_source=newsnetwork&amp;utm_medium=l&amp;utm_content=content&amp;utm_campaign=mayoclinic&amp;geo=national&amp;placementsite=enterprise&amp;cauid=100721" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dr. Megan Wasson,</a>&nbsp;a gynecologic surgeon at Mayo Clinic, specializes in&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/tests-procedures/minimally-invasive-surgery/about/pac-20384771" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">minimally invasive surgery</a>. She says the decision to undergo a hysterectomy is highly individualized, based on each patient's specific needs.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In many cases, a minimally invasive approach is an effective treatment. This type of surgery can help patients heal faster with less pain and a shorter recovery.</p>



<p><strong><a href="https://youtu.be/l2AgnVgivok" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Watch: The Mayo Clinic Minute</a></strong></p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<div class="fluidEmbed"><iframe loading="lazy" id="videoidhttpsyoutubel2AgnVgivok" title="Mayo Clinic Minute - Minimally invasive hysterectomy" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/l2AgnVgivok?feature=oembed&amp;enablejsapi=1" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen=""></iframe></div>
</div></figure>



<p><strong>Journalists: Broadcast-quality video (1:00) is in the downloads at the end of this post. Please courtesy: "Mayo Clinic News Network." Read the&nbsp;<a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/10/SCRIPT-MCM-Minimally-invasive-hysterectomy.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">script</a>.</strong></p>



<p>Minimally invasive surgery uses small incisions and special tools, causing less damage to the body than traditional surgery.&nbsp;</p>



<p>"Any minimally invasive approach, whether that's vaginal, laparoscopic, robotic — that's going to be associated with a very fast recovery. The vast majority of the time, patients are able to leave the hospital the same day," explains Dr. Wasson.</p>



<p>The most common gynecologic surgery is hysterectomy — the removal of the uterus.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-full"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="550" height="309" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2017/10/hysterectomy.jpg" alt="medical illustration of the various types of hysterectomies" class="wp-image-174317" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2017/10/hysterectomy.jpg 550w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2017/10/hysterectomy-300x169.jpg 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 550px) 100vw, 550px"></figure></div>


<p>"The vast majority of the time we are able to complete hysterectomy through a minimally invasive approach. The most minimally invasive is a vaginal hysterectomy, which does not require any incisions on the abdomen," she says.</p>



<p>Laparoscopic hysterectomy is another approach.</p>



<p>"We separate the uterus from all of the surrounding tissue, and then we remove it. And then we do still need to do a hysterectomy through a larger incision called a laparotomy, at times. Most commonly that's going to be in the setting of a cancer or if there are extremely large fibroids," says Dr. Wasson.</p>



<p>Dr. Wasson says treatment is not one-size-fits-all, and she encourages patients to ask their healthcare team questions.</p>



